###📰 Bharat Herald Digital Transformation Analysis
##📌 Project Overview

This project was completed as part of the Codebasics Resume Challenge, focusing on Bharat Herald — a 70-year-old newspaper facing decline in the post-COVID digital era.

Using 5 years of operational and financial data, the goal was to analyze the drop in print circulation, declining ad revenue, and evaluate opportunities for digital transformation.

##🎯 Objectives


Analyze print circulation trends (2019–2024)


Identify high-performing and underperforming cities


Evaluate ad revenue trends across categories


Assess print inefficiencies (waste & returns)


Measure digital pilot performance


Recommend a data-driven digital strategy



##📊 Key Insights
#📉 Print Decline


Circulation dropped from 1.2M+ to <560K copies


Overall decline of ~25% in recent years


#🧾 Print Inefficiency


Print waste reached ~10%


Jaipur had highest circulation and highest inefficiency


#💰 Revenue Trends


Ad revenue declined across most categories


Strong dependency on government & real estate ads


#🏙️ City-Level Insights


Patna → Highest ROI (stable ads + digital engagement)


Jaipur → High waste, needs optimization


Varanasi, Lucknow, Kanpur → High digital readiness


#📱 Digital Pilot Findings


High bounce rates (poor UX)


Low engagement despite investment


Clear mismatch between product and user behavior



##🚀 Strategic Recommendations
Phase 1: Relaunch (0–6 months)


Mobile-first platform


WhatsApp-based news delivery


Focus on high-readiness cities


Phase 2: Content Transformation (6–18 months)


Short videos, podcasts, infographics


Regional & vernacular content strategy


Phase 3: Monetization & Scale (18+ months)


Subscription model


Loyalty programs


Pay-per-article system



##🛠️ Tools & Technologies


Python (Data Analysis)


